content: Nerve damage or diabetic peripheral neuropathy is one of the long-term complication of diabetes. If left untreated, the damage caused by neuropathy can potentially lead to infection and limb amputation. Fortunately, there are several steps you can take to prevent nerve damage. Along with regular foot checks, controlling your blood sugar levels can improve the symptoms of neuropathy and can delay the progression of nerve damage. http://dbts.ca/72my50Azlns

Sooooo I don‚Äôt say much here because I‚Äôm more of an observer and I like to take things in before I just jump I guess. Hi my name is Ny‚ÄôShara and I‚Äôm 20 years old. I got diagnosed in 2018 and I ended up in the ICU for a few weeks where I almost died. My A1v was incredibly high. I was on so many medications and insulin drip for days. After I finally got out of the ICU I was depressed and I got into a car accident a week later. 2018 was a very rough year. Things went down hill. From the ICU to depression to the car accident to be kicked out of my house to being on all of these new diabetic medications to being poor to not going to college and not knowing my major. My point of making this is that I didn‚Äôt want to change at first. I also didn‚Äôt know how to. The only one I really had was my sisters and brother and my mom and grandma sometimes. And my long distance boyfriend who lives in Cali while I in Michigan for a year. I also don‚Äôt like asking for help lol. I was a vegetarian and I lovedddd carbs. My point of making this is that I went to a diabetes retreat. I meet people who actually knew what I was going through and didn‚Äôt make me feel insane and then I found these groups here on Facebook. And I saw that I could change. Now I‚Äôm a pollotarian and I don‚Äôt drink or eat sugar anymore. I left the carbs and I‚Äôm eating much better. I‚Äôm working again and I‚Äôm better with my family. My boyfriend and I aren‚Äôt doing LDR right now and we‚Äôre almost to our three year. I‚Äôm going to college this winter and I figured out that I‚Äôm gonna be a double major in communications and creative writing with a vet assist certificate. And yesterday my doctor said I lost 10 pounds from the beginning of the year and my A1c level went from 9.1 last year to 6.4 currently! I‚Äôm doing better and it took me a long time to get here but you can‚Äôt help someone who doesn‚Äôt wanna be helped. I used to be that someone. Or at least I didn‚Äôt know how to ask. I hope someone sees this and knows that you can do anything if you trust yourself and want better things for yourself. Even with this pandemic it‚Äôll get better. Thank you for listening if anyone did. üòÇ ahhhh Im so excited!! Okay sorry. This is long enough. ‚ò∫Ô∏è we got this.

Possible trigger for some  . . . . . . . On 29th June my mum, whom I‚Äôm her full time carer for, was taken to hospital by ambulance for a chest infection which turned out to be pneumonia, she has pulmonary fibrosis, emphysema, asthma, kidney failure & type 2 diabetes. However due to her symptoms they had to presume she had the coronavirus until she tested negative, which she did. Due to this wait for her test results I was not allowed to visit her for 4 days. The first day I was allowed into visit her the first thing I noticed was her feet were the size of balloons, she couldn‚Äôt even put her slippers on. I asked mum if she had been taking three of her heart medications to which she recalled that she had not. So I immediately alerted the nurse who responded that ‚Äúwe‚Äù Took her off her heart medications because she had low blood pressure. However she only takes one medication for BP and the rest for diastolic dysfunction and SVT. I got extremely angry at this because not only did they not consult a cardiologist they didn‚Äôt even consult a doctor or myself before ceasing this medication. Then later on I find out that the emergency doctor did not chart one of her heart medications even though I have provided the paramedics with a list of her medications, their dose, frequency and the illness it was treating together with a list of her medical conditions, medical history and the paramedics took Mum‚Äôs entire tray of medications all of which had her name and the medication. So there should have been absolutely no excuse for this to happen. Mum was discharged from hospital on 7th July and went downhill extremely quickly. I called an ambulance again a week later and after numerous tests the right side of her heart is failing and in the seven days she has been in hospital she has gained 8 kg (17 pounds) which I can only presume is in fluid. both her Cardiologist and Lung Specialist have told her that she is dying and her Lung Specialist told me that once they deem her palliative care she will immediately go into a coma. The cardiologist has put her on at least 12 new medications but because of the selfishness of many people in Melbourne, Australia we are back in lockdown and our hospitals have a strict no visitor policy. I have been trying to get an exemption for visitation due to me being a caregiver and there is care that I provide to my mother at the hospital is not currently providing such as her daily foot exercises for her mobility and balance, her multiple times a day leg massages to assist with circulation and mobility As she is a diabetic and has associated neuropathic and also a history of blood clots and DVT. Because she is currently not deemed palliative I‚Äôm not allowed to visit. The hospital advised me to see a solicitor so I‚Äôve spoken to 4 different lawfirms however this stuff is taking a lot of time and time I may not have. I also contacted my local member of Parliament who was amazing at trying to help however the executive of the hospital, who is a jerk and very dismissive when I spoke to him, will not allow exemption for me. Even though I tested negative to the coronavirus yesterday I‚Äôm not allowed to visit. Yet people who have outpatient appointment at the specialist rooms also on the hospital site Are allowed to enter the hospital without proof of a negative test walk down the corridor walk through a ward down another corridor before they reach the consulting suites and they aren‚Äôt allowing me precious quality time with my mother?! ü§¨ü§¨ü§¨  After dropping off some clean clothes for mum at the hospital which I was allowed to walk into the foyer without being checked a kitchen staff member came up the loft from the staff Carpark without a mask on!!! SERIOUSLY!!! Anyways I managed to find my mums room and barely saw her face through the dirty windows.  Anyways I‚Äôd like some help, information etc on heart failure or diastolic dysfunction. I‚Äôm happy for people to private message me if they don‚Äôt wish to respond publicly.

I must confess that I was very careless with my type 2 diabetes for many years, which has led to severe numbness, burning and tingling in my feet and toes, due to neuropathy. I have finally made a huge effort to control my eating and intake of alcohol and have very recently managed to bring down my blood sugar levels considerably. I am told however that the damage to my feet is irreparable and cannot be reversed. Is there anything I can do to alleviate the pain and to restore better feeling and sensitivity in my toes and more importantly to ensure that any further neuropathy is slowed down?

I am a new member here.  Thank you for accepting my request.   I have had neuropathy since 2003.  However, it was only about a 1. Back in January I found out I had a Brenners tumor that was malignant.  I had surgery to remove the tumor in early February and chemio started end of February.  After the 3rd chemo treatment I was unable to stand or walk.  Chemo attacked my neuropathy all over my body.  I demanded chemo stop and give me a break.  It has taken from May until now to walk decently.   Very scary! I still have a long way to go to get back where I was, if that is possible.  A Walker has helped me greatly to walk and get some strength back.   Chemo first attacked my knees.  My knees became so weak.  I am waiting to talk with an orthopedic doctor about my knees.  My fingertips are numb and my toes are even more so.   Never had this before chemo. Has anyone else ever  encountered chemo attacking your neuropathy in this way?

A woman awakes during the night to find that her husband was not in their bed. She puts on her robe and goes downstairs to look for him. She finds him sitting at the kitchen table with a cup of coffee in front him. He appears deep in thought, just staring at the wall. She watches as he wipes a tear from his eye and takes a sip of coffee. "What's the matter, dear?" she whispers as she steps into the room. "Why are you down here at this time of night?" The husband looks up, "Do you remember 20 years ago when we were dating, and you were only 17?" he asks solemnly. The wife is touched thinking her husband is so caring and sensitive. "Yes, I do," she replies. The husband pauses. The words are not coming easily. "Do you remember when you father caught us in the back seat of my car?" "Yes, I remember," says the wife, lowering herself into a chair beside him. The husband continues..."Do you remember when he shoved a shotgun in my face and said, "Either you marry my daughter, or I will send you to jail for 20 years". "I remember that too", she replies softly. He wipes another tear from his cheek and says... "I would have been released today if I went to the jail!!
